# Git commit and push (github-bin)

After completing requested code changes in this repository, **commit and push automatically**. Do not ask the user to commit unless they explicitly say not to.

## Commit message format

Write the message yourself (subject + body). Do not use a one-word or empty message.

```
Short imperative subject (≤72 chars)

2–4 sentences: what changed, why, and any user-visible behavior.
Mention script version from the top changelog line when editing *.sh files.
```

Example:

```
signal-install.sh v1.6: release dates in version check; update prompt default [y/N]

Fetch published_at from GitHub for installed and latest signal-cli versions.
Show dates in the version check block. Change the update prompt to [y/N]
so Enter defaults to skipping the upgrade.
```

## Workflow

1. `git status`, `git diff`, `git log -3 --oneline` before committing.
2. Stage only files that belong to the task.
3. Commit with subject + body (see below for Windows).
4. `git push` to the current branch (usually `master`).
5. Report the commit hash and one-line subject to the user.

## Windows / PowerShell

Do **not** use `git commit -m "..."` inline in PowerShell (messages get mangled).

Use a short-lived bash script in the repo, run with Git Bash, then delete it:

```bash
#!/usr/bin/env bash
cd "$(dirname "$0")"
git add <files>
git commit -F - <<'EOF'
Subject line here

Body paragraph(s) here.
EOF
git push origin master
```

Or `git commit -F /path/to/msg.txt` after writing the message to a file.

## Changelog

When editing shell scripts, add a dated version line at the top (`# YYYY.MM.DD - v. X.Y - ...`) and reflect that version in the commit subject.
